## 3. Data Model

### 3.1. CSV Input Format (HubSpot Export)

The CSV exported from HubSpot has these columns:

|Column|CSV Header|Description|
|---|---|---|
|A|Record ID|HubSpot internal ID|
|B|Deal Name|Company/client name|
|C|Deal Stage|Pipeline stage (raw from HubSpot)|
|D|Close Date|Expected close date|
|E|Deal owner|Sales rep name|
|F|Amount|Deal value (often empty)|

### 3.2. Stage Mapping

The HubSpot CSV contains various stages. Map them to the presentation stages as follows:

```typescript
const STAGE_MAPPING: Record<string, string> = {
  "First Outreach": "First Outreach",
  "Intro Call Scheduled": "Call Scheduled",
  "Qualifying": "Qualifying",
  "Client Internal Review": "Client Internal Review",
  "scope definition": "Scope Definition",    // Note: lowercase in CSV
  "Proposal Sent": "Proposal Sent",
  "Closed Won (Integration)": "Closed Won",  // Note: includes suffix in CSV
};
```

**Important:** Any stage NOT in this mapping must be **filtered out** of the presentation. Stages like `Lead`, `Later FUP`, `No Response / Stale`, and `Disqualified` are excluded.

### 3.3. Presentation Column Order

Columns must appear left-to-right in this exact order:

1. First Outreach
2. Call Scheduled
3. Qualifying
4. Client Internal Review
5. Scope Definition
6. Proposal Sent
7. Closed Won

### 3.4. TypeScript Interfaces

```typescript
interface Deal {
  recordId: string;
  dealName: string;        // Company name from CSV
  dealStage: string;       // Mapped presentation stage
  rawStage: string;        // Original CSV stage
  closeDate: string;
  dealOwner: string;
  amount: string;
  category: string;        // MVP: mocked — e.g. "Fintech", "Insurance", "Retail"
  type: "Customer" | "Channel"; // MVP: mocked
  logoUrl: string;         // Resolved logo URL
}

interface PresentationData {
  date: string;            // Presentation date (dd/mm/yyyy)
  deals: Deal[];
  scores: {
    totalDeals: number;    // All deals in visible stages
    customers: number;     // Deals where type === "Customer"
    channels: number;      // Deals where type === "Channel"
  };
}
```

### 3.5. Mock Data for Category and Type (MVP)

Since the CSV does not yet have `Category` and `Type` columns, generate mock values:

```typescript
// Category: randomly assign from this list based on deal name (keep consistent per company)
const CATEGORIES = ["Fintech", "Insurance", "Retail", "Logistics", "Agritech", "SaaS", "Banking", "Payments"];

// Type: assign "Customer" to ~70% of deals, "Channel" to ~30%
// Use a deterministic method (e.g., hash of deal name) so the same deal always gets the same type
```

---

## 4. Logo Resolution Strategy

### 4.1. Primary Source — GitHub Repository

Logos are stored in a public GitHub repository. The naming convention for logo files:

```
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/{OWNER}/{REPO}/main/logos/{slug}.png
```

Where `{slug}` is the company name normalized:

- Lowercase
- Remove accents and special characters
- Replace spaces with hyphens
- Remove suffixes like "Banco", "Bank", parenthetical content

Examples:

|Deal Name|Slug|
|---|---|
|99 PAY|99|
|Banco BV|bv|
|Banco BS2|bs2|
|Porto Seguro|porto-seguro|
|ifood|ifood|
|Natura / Emana Pay|natura|
|interbank (peru)|interbank|
|MercadoBitcoin (MB)|mercadobitcoin|
|PlugZ (Semenzato)|plugz|
|UY3 (canal BaaS)|uy3|
|Grupo Primo (primo rico)|grupo-primo|
|CRM Bonus + Havan: ...|crm-bonus|

### 4.2. Fallback — Favicon API

If the GitHub logo returns a 404, use Google Favicons as fallback:

```
https://www.google.com/s2/favicons?domain={domain}&sz=128
```

For this, maintain a `DOMAIN_MAP` dictionary that maps deal names to website domains:

```typescript
const DOMAIN_MAP: Record<string, string> = {
  "99": "99app.com",
  "ifood": "ifood.com.br",
  "Itaú": "itau.com.br",
  "Magalu": "magazineluisa.com.br",
  // ... etc
};
```

### 4.3. Final Fallback — Initial Letter Avatar

If both GitHub and Favicon fail, render a colored square with the first letter(s) of the company name. Use a deterministic color based on the company name hash.

