## 5. UI/UX Specification

### 5.1. General Design Rules

- **Target resolution:** 1920×1080 (optimized for desktop presentation mode)
- **Background:** Dark (`#1A1A1A` or similar very dark gray, almost black)
- **Text:** White (`#FFFFFF`) and muted gray (`#888888`) for labels
- **Accent:** Green (`#4CAF50` or Magie brand green `#4ADE80`)
- **Font:** Inter or system sans-serif
- **Layout:** Full viewport, no scrolling on the presentation board — content must fit
- **Border radius on logos:** `8px` (rounded squares)

### 5.2. Cover Page (`/`)

The cover page is the entry point. Layout:

- **Dark background** matching the main theme
- **Centered card** (approx 960×600px) with slightly lighter dark bg (`#262626`)
- **Inside the card (left side):**
    - Magie logo (top-left)
    - Title: **"B2B Deal Presentation"** in bold white
    - Date input: labeled "Presentation Date", format `dd/mm/yyyy`, with calendar icon
    - Upload button: green button **"Upload Hubspot Deals file"** — triggers file picker for `.csv`
    - After upload: show filename below the button
    - Horizontal separator line
    - **"Let's go!"** button — disabled/gray until both date and file are provided; green when active
- **Right side of card:** decorative 3D green Magie hat illustration (use a static image or CSS gradient placeholder)

### 5.3. Presentation Board (`/presentation`)

#### Header Section

- **Top-left:** Magie logo icon + **"DEALS"** in large bold caps + subtitle "ALL HANDS • {date}" in muted gray
- **Top-right:** Score badges in pill/rounded-rect shapes:
    - `🎯 DEALS | {count}` — total deals across all visible stages
    - `🏢 CUSTOMERS | {count}` — deals with type "Customer"
    - `🔗 CHANNELS | {count}` — deals with type "Channel"
    - Each badge has a dark bg with subtle border, icon on left, label, pipe separator, and count

#### Column Headers

- Row of column headers below the header section
- Each header: stage name in **bold uppercase** white text
- Separated by subtle vertical dividers or equal spacing
- Columns are evenly distributed across the viewport width

#### Deal Grid (Logo Grid)

- Below column headers, each column contains a grid of logo cards
- **Logo cards:** Square tiles (~56–64px), rounded corners (8px), containing the company logo
- Cards are arranged in a grid within each column (3–4 per row depending on column width)
- **No company name text** — logos only
- Logos should have a subtle dark border or shadow to stand out on the dark background
- Cards should have a hover effect (slight scale up, brightness increase)

#### Client Detail Overlay

- **Triggered by:** clicking any logo card
- **Position:** Fixed right-side panel (approx 300px wide), full height, with dark bg (`#1E1E1E`)
- **Content:**
    - Close button (X) at top-right
    - Stage badge at top (e.g., "FIRST OUTREACH" in a green/yellow pill)
    - Company logo (larger, ~48px) + Company name in bold white
    - Info fields (label in gray, value in white):
        - **Category:** e.g., "Fintech"
        - **Type:** e.g., "Customer"
        - **Deal Owner:** e.g., "Leonardo Rosa"
- **Animation:** Slide in from right, 200ms ease-out
- **Backdrop:** Optional subtle darken overlay on the left side

### 5.4. Responsive Behavior

This is a **desktop-only presentation tool**. No need for mobile responsiveness. Target:

- Minimum width: 1280px
- Optimal: 1920×1080
- Logo grid should adapt: fewer columns of logos if viewport is narrower

---

## 6. Implementation Rules

### 6.1. CSV Parsing

- Use **PapaParse** for CSV parsing (handles quoted fields, commas in values, etc.)
- Parse on the client side (no backend needed for MVP)
- Strip quotes from all fields
- Handle edge cases:
    - Empty `Amount` fields
    - Missing `Close Date`
    - Case-insensitive stage matching (e.g., "scope definition" vs "Scope Definition")

### 6.2. State Management

- Use **React Context** or **Zustand** to store:
    - Parsed deals array
    - Presentation date
    - Selected deal (for overlay)
    - Loading/error states

### 6.3. Routing

- `/` — Cover page (upload form)
- `/presentation` — Presentation board
- After CSV is parsed and processed, navigate to `/presentation`
- If user navigates to `/presentation` without data, redirect back to `/`

### 6.4. Performance

- Logo images should use `next/image` with lazy loading
- Add `loading="lazy"` for off-screen logos
- Handle broken images gracefully (show fallback avatar)
- CSV parsing should show a brief loading state

### 6.5. Code Style

- Use **functional components** with hooks
- Prefer **named exports**
- Use **Tailwind CSS** utility classes (avoid custom CSS files where possible)
- TypeScript strict mode enabled
- All data types must have explicit interfaces
- Use descriptive variable names in English
- UI text (labels, titles) in **English** to match the Figma design
- Comments can be in English or Portuguese

---

## 7. Step-by-Step Build Plan

Follow this order when implementing the project:

### Phase 1 — Project Setup

1. Initialize Next.js project with TypeScript and Tailwind
2. Configure `tailwind.config.ts` with dark theme colors
3. Set up project folder structure
4. Install PapaParse (`npm install papaparse @types/papaparse`)

### Phase 2 — Data Layer

5. Create `types.ts` with all interfaces
6. Create `constants.ts` with stage mappings, column order, categories, domain map
7. Create `parseCSV.ts` — function that takes raw CSV text, returns `PresentationData`
8. Create `logoResolver.ts` — function that resolves logo URL for a deal name
9. Create mock generators for `category` and `type`

### Phase 3 — Cover Page

10. Build `CoverPage.tsx` with date input, file upload, and "Let's go!" button
11. Style to match the Figma mockup (dark card, green buttons)
12. Wire up CSV parsing on file upload
13. Navigate to `/presentation` on "Let's go!" click

### Phase 4 — Presentation Board

14. Build `Header.tsx` with logo, title, date, and score badges
15. Build `ScoreBadge.tsx` component
16. Build `DealColumn.tsx` — renders column header + grid of logo cards
17. Build `DealCard.tsx` — single logo tile with hover effects and click handler
18. Build `PresentationBoard.tsx` — orchestrates columns and layout
19. Wire up real data from store/context

### Phase 5 — Detail Overlay

20. Build `ClientDetailOverlay.tsx` — right-side slide-in panel
21. Add click handlers on `DealCard` to open overlay
22. Add close button and backdrop click to dismiss

### Phase 6 — Logo Pipeline

23. Set up GitHub repository for logos
24. Implement fallback chain: GitHub → Favicon → Letter Avatar
25. Add `onError` handlers for broken images

### Phase 7 — Polish

26. Add transitions/animations (overlay slide, card hover)
27. Test with real HubSpot CSV export
28. Edge case handling (empty columns, many deals in one stage)
29. Ensure everything fits in 1920×1080 without scrolling

---

## 8. Known Edge Cases

- **"scope definition"** in CSV is lowercase — normalize before matching
- **"Closed Won (Integration)"** — match with `startsWith("Closed Won")`
- **"Intro Call Scheduled"** → maps to **"Call Scheduled"** in presentation
- Some deal names contain extra context in parentheses: `"UY3 (canal BaaS)"`, `"interbank (peru)"` — strip parenthetical content for logo slug resolution
- Some deal names contain slashes: `"Natura / Emana Pay"` — use first part for logo
- Some deal names contain colons: `"CRM Bonus + Havan: debt collection"` — use first part before colon/plus
- **Empty columns** are still shown with just the header (no logos underneath)
- Deal owner field is used as-is from CSV (no normalization needed)

